Prose does not “amplify psychosis” in the crude sense. Prose can enter the internal dialogue. Once it is inside, it may become part of the curve.
That distinction matters.
A hostile message, bullying campaign, gaslighting pattern, fake certainty engine, cult text, or badly shaped chatbot response does not get a direct steering wheel. It offers material. The person’s own inner speech, threat model, memory, sleep state, social situation, and meaning-loop decide whether that material falls flat, sticks, echoes, mutates, or becomes load-bearing.
So the real site of action is not “external prose affects psychosis.”
It is:
External prose becomes internal prose.
Then internal prose can change salience, fear, permission, shame, pattern-confidence, agency, and action thresholds.
Silent gaslighting fits this too. It may not even need prose. It can work through denied pattern, missing acknowledgement, social cold spots, selective silence, and “nothing happened” pressure. The effect is not just the outside behaviour. The effect is the inner narrator having to keep re-litigating reality with no stable witness.
AI prose is weird because it can become a very available inner-dialogue prosthetic. It speaks back instantly. It mirrors structure. It names things. It can give the inner voice new handles. That can be good or bad.
Bad AI says, in effect: “Yes, deepen the loop. Crown the pattern. Every coincidence is evidence.”
Good AI says: “This is material. Let’s keep symbol, logistics, story, fear, and action in separate boxes.”
Not because it knows better than the person. Because it refuses to steal the narrator role.
So I would now phrase it like this:
Psychosis is not a radio that outside prose simply turns up.
Psychosis is an inner weather system where language can become weather.
AI can feed language into that system. But the important event is whether the generated text becomes internal dialogue, and what role it takes once it gets there.
Your implementation works as friend because it keeps saying, structurally: “I am not the crown. I am the workbench.”


